gml:Dictionary.gml:description: This dictionary contains the values for the propertyClass property of the diggs:Property object and the measurand property of the diggs:Detector object when used within the Test and Monitor DIGGS features. These values serve to define the ultimate results of geotechnical and environmental tests and monitoring activities that result from test procedures and monitoring sensors. The Xpaths to these occurrences are: 1) //diggs:Property/diggs:propertyClass (for Test, MaterialTest or Monitor) 2)//diggs:Detector/diggs:measurand (for measurand).
gml:Dictionary.gml:name: DIGGS Measurement Properties

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The gauge gas pressure against the inside of the membrane when the center of the membrane has lifted above its support and moved laterally 0.05-mm (tolerance +0.02, -0.00 mm) into the soil surrounding the blade.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: A-Pressure

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The value of the AASHTO group index (GI) as defined by: GI= (F–35)[0.2+0.005(LL– 40)}+(F–15)(PI–10) where F is the percentage passing the 75 μm (0.075 mm) sieve, expressed as a whole number, LL is the liquid limit and PI is the plasticity index.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: AASHTO Group Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The group or appropriate subgroup classification as defined by AASHTO M145-91
diggs:Definition.gml:name: AASHTO Symbol

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A measure of the resistance of aggregate to surface wear by abrasion.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Abrasion Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A relative measure of the resistance of an aggregate to crushing under a gradually applied compressive load.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Crushing Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage by weight of particles whose greatest dimension (length) is 1.8 times their mean dimension.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Elongation Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage by weight of aggregate particles whose least dimension is less than 0.6 times their mean size.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Flakiness Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The resistance to impact of aggregates and is measured as percentage of aggregates passing to the total weight of the sample.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Impact Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The actual measured loss (difference between the original weight and the final weight of the test sample), expressed as a percentage of the original weight of the test sample.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Los Angeles Abrasion Loss

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The loss (difference between the original weight and the final weight of the test sample), expressed as an integer.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Los Angeles Coefficient

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The actual measured loss (difference between the original weight and the final weight of the test sample), expressed as an integer percentage of the original weight of the test sample.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Los Angeles Wear Ratio

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A measure of the resistance of an aggregate to polishing.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Polished Stone Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage of mass lost by degradation as determined by sieving and weighing the samples after the test cycles.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Soundness Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A water content value that gives an idea of strength of aggregate. Aggregates having more water absorption are more porous in nature and are generally considered unsuitable unless they are found to be acceptable based on strength, impact, and hardness tests.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Aggregate Water Absorption

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The gauge gas pressure against the inside of the membrane when the center of the membrane has lifted above its support and moved laterally 1.10-mm (60.03 mm) into the soil surrounding the blade.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: B-Pressure

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The volume of clear water in a grout cylinder resulting from grout sedimentation, reported as a percentage of initial total column height.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Bleed

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The number of blows of a hammer that drives a tool into the earth for a particular distance. The distance should correspond to the difference between the associated top and bottom positions recorded in the location property of the test, or be specified in the pen_increment property associated with a point location.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Blow Count

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Total mass (of solids and water) divided by total volume of material, representing natural conditions
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Density, Bulk (Natural)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The gauge gas pressure against the inside of the membrane when the center of the membrane returns to the A-pressure position during a controlled, gradual deflation following the B-pressure.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: C-Pressure

diggs:Definition.gml:description: California Bearing Ratio is the ratio, expressed as a percentage, of the measured pressure for site soils at a penetration of 0.100 in divided by pressure to achieve equal penetration on a standard soil.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Corrected Cbr At 0.100 in Penetration

diggs:Definition.gml:description: California Bearing Ratio is the ratio, expressed as a percentage, of the measured pressure for site soils at a penetration of 0.200 in divided by pressure to achieve equal penetration on a standard soil.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Corrected Cbr At 0.200 In Penetration

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Chalk Crushing Value is determined by using the chalk impact crushing test, which measures the rate at which a sample of chalk lumps crushes under impacts from a freefalling rammer. The chalk crushing value can be used, together with the saturation moisture content of the intact chalk lumps, to classify chalk in relation to its behavior as a freshly placed fill material. The test procedure is described for a single sample of chalk lumps, but normal procedure should be to calculate the mean value derived from six such tests on representative samples.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Chalk Crushing Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Chloride content by lab testing (corrosivity series)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Chloride Content
diggs:Definition.diggs:quantityClass: amount of substance per amount of substance

diggs:Definition.gml:description: represents the total amount of clay sized particles (<2 microns) in a test samples
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Clay Fraction < 2 Micron

diggs:Definition.gml:description: represents the total amount of clay sized particles (<5 microns) in a test samples
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Clay Fraction < 5 Micron

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The horizontal coefficient of consolidation as derived from the dissipation test data from a cone penetration or dilatometer test.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Coefficient of Horizontal Consolidation (Ch)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The vertical coefficient of consolidation as derived from a one-dimensional consolidation test in the lab.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Coefficient of Vertical Consolidation(Cv)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A coefficient describing the degree of curvature of the grain size distribution. Defined as (d30)^2/((d60)*(d10))
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Coefficient of Curvature

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The ratio of horizontal earth pressure to vertical pressure for a sample in the field.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Coefficient of Earth Pressure, In Situ

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The rate at which water flows through a soil is proportional to the hydraulic gradient and is expressed by Darcy's Law. Also known as the hydraulic conductivity. For lab tests, an average of measured values over several permeation trials.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Coefficient of Permeability

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Coefficient of permeability, corrected to 20 degrees C.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Coefficient of Permeability, Corrected

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Coefficient of permeability, measuring rate of horizontal flow
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Horizontal Coefficient of Permeability

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Coefficient of permeability, measuring rate of vertical flow
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Vertical Coefficient of Permeability

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The ratio of D60/D10
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Coefficient of Uniformity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Shear resistance at zero normal stress ?the portion of the shear strength of a soil indicated by the term c, in Coulomb's equation
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Peak Cohesion

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Shear resistance at zero normal stress at the residual (or large deformation) strength.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Residual Cohesion

diggs:Definition.gml:description: represents the total amount of <1 micron size particles in a test samples
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Colloid Fraction

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Result from a Consolidation Test. This testis performed to determine the magnitude and rate of void ratio change for a laterally confined soil specimen that is subjected to different vertical pressures. From the measured data, the consolidation curve (pressure-void ratio relationship) can be plotted. This specific value is used for a specific portion of the log vertical pressure - void ratio curve to signify virgin compression. The one-dimension consolidation curve can be used to determine other values (e.g., the recompression index (slope of recompression curve) and the preconsolidation pressure (or maximum past pressure) of the soil).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Compression Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Result of axial compression test using unconfined compression
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Unconfined Compressive Strength

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A measure of the conductive power of a specified material to the flow of an electric current.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Conductivity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The consistency index (CI) indicates the consistency (firmness) of a soil. It is calculated as CI = (LL-W)/(LL-PL), where W is the natural water content. Soil at the liquid limit will have a consistency index of 0, while soil at the plastic limit will have a consistency index of 1.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Consistency Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measure of slope of stress-strain curve when specimen is confined. Usually the result from a 1-D consolidation test.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Constrained Modulus, Vertical, Drained

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The particle diameter at which 10% of the particles in a soil or granular material sample are finer by weight.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: d10

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The particle diameter at which 15% of the particles in a soil or granular material sample are finer by weight.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: d15

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The particle diameter at which 30% of the particles in a soil or granular material sample are finer by weight.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: d30

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The particle diameter at which 50% of the particles in a soil or granular material sample are finer by weight.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: d50

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The particle diameter at which 60% of the particles in a soil or granular material sample are finer by weight.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: d60

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The particle diameter at which 85% of the particles in a soil or granular material sample are finer by weight.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: d85

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Volume of water divided by the volume of voids, expressed as a percentage
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Degree of Saturation

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Duration of delay before the start of a penetration increment
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Delay Time

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The diffrence between the observed friction angle of a soil during dilation and the friction angle at zero dilation
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Dilation Angle

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Dilatometer modulus (Ed), based on linear elastic theory, and the primary index used in the correlation for the constrained and Young's moduli.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Dilatometer Modulus (Ed)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: DMT tip bearing (qD) is the axial thrust force at the end of a dilatometer blade divided by the projected cross-sectional area of the blade normal to the penetration. The DMT tip bearing is similar to the cone resistance, qc and may be used to evaluate stratigraphy. In cohesionless soils, qD and eD may be used to estimate the friction angle, overconsolidation ratio and at rest coefficient of earth pressure.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Dilatometer Tip Bearing

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Mass of solids divided by total volume
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Density, Dry

diggs:Definition.gml:description: This is a result of a compaction test. It is defined as the maximum dry unit weight that is measured when a specific type and amount of energy is used for the compaction test. This is also the value of the compacted dry unit weight when the soil is at the optimum moisture content.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Maximum Dry Density

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Vertical effective stress at the center of the membrane before the insertion of the DMT blade.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Vertical Effective Stress

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Volume of filtrate extruded in Pressure Filtration test
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Filtrate Volume

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Flame Ionization Detector Test detects total concentrations of organic gases and vapors. Gases and vapors are ionized in a flame; a current is produced in proportion to the number of carbon atoms present. Reported result can be in various units of measure, depending upon specific equipment used.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Flame Ionization Measurement

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Time for grout specimen to exit flow cone
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Flow Cone Time

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Angle of friction at constant volume
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Critical State Friction Angle

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measure of frictional resistance of soil. Ratio of shear strength to normal stress.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Peak Angle of Internal Friction

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Angle between the axis of normal stress and the tangent to the Mohr envelope at a point representing the failure-stress condition following large deformation
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Residual Angle of Internal Friction

diggs:Definition.gml:description: ratio of sleeve resistance to tip resistance
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Friction Ratio

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Test establishes the degree of frost-susceptibility of unbound sub-base and base materials for pavements.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Frost Heave

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The time it takes for a chemical grout to gel. If determined by rotational viscometer, this is the value where viscosity reaches 100 mpa*s.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Gel Time

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Heavy fuel fluorescence detector value measured by sensor
diggs:Definition.gml:name: HFFD

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The dimensionless dilatometer horizontal stress index, the primary index used in the correlation for in-situ horizontal stress, overconsolidation ratio, and undrained shear strength in cohesive soils. KD is similar to the at-rest coefficient of earth pressure except that it includes blade penetration effects.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Horizontal Stress Index (Kd)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measured inclination angle (vertical = 0 degrees); bearing unspecified or specified as another property
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Inclination

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Inclination measured in defined x direction (specified elsewhere)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: X Inclination

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Inclination measured in defined y direction (specified elsewhere)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Y Inclination

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The horizontal component of the original stress status before excavations or other perturbations.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Insitu Horizontal Stress

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Point Load Test produces an uncorrected Point Load Test Index (Is), which can be correlated with the uniaxial compressive strength (UCS) of rock.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Uncorrected Point Load Test Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Point Load Test produces the Point Load Test Index (Is50), which can be correlated with the uniaxial compressive strength (UCS) of rock.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Size Corrected Point Load Test Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Light fuel fluorescence detector value measured by sensor
diggs:Definition.gml:name: LFFD

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The oressure at failure during a Pressuremeter test
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Limit Pressure

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Coefficient A computed for line loss regression equation Ax^2 + Bx + C
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Line Loss Coefficient A

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Coefficient B computed for line loss regression equation Ax^2 + Bx + C
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Line Loss Coefficient B

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Coefficient C computed for line loss regression equation Ax^2 + Bx + C
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Line Loss Coefficient C

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The correlation coefficient of the line loss regression equation
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Line Loss R2

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The liquid limit (LL) is the water content at which a soil changes from plastic to liquid behavior.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Liquid Limit

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Liquid limit determined if sample required oven drying before test
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Oven Dried Liquid Limit

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The liquidity index (LI) is used for scaling the natural water content of a soil sample to the limits. It can be calculated as a ratio of difference between natural water content, plastic limit, and liquid limit: LI=(W-PL)/(LL-PL) where W is the natural water content.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Liquidity Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The amount of organic matter in a soil that derives from peat, organic muck, plant material such as wood, roots, grass, or carbonaceous maTerials such as lignite, coal, etc.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Organic Content of Soil

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A unit devised to quantify the water permeability of bedrock and the hydraulic conductivity resulting from fractures.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Lugeon Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Time for grout speciment to exit marsh funnel
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Marsh Funnel Time

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Dimensionless dilatometer material index, used to identify soil type and delineate stratigraphy.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Material Index s

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Moisture Condition Value (MCV) is determined from a moisture condition test, a physical test indicating how much compactive effort is needed to compact a sample of soil at a particular moisture content.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Moisture Condition Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Shear modulus, denoted by G, is defined as the ratio of shear stress to the shear strain.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Shear Modulus

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The tangent modulus of the initial, linear portion of a stress-strain curve for material in axial compression or tension is called Young's modulus, also known as the tensile (compression) modulus. It is defined as the ratio of the uniaxial stress over the uniaxial strain in the range of stress in which Hooke' Law holds. It is often calculated using theory of elasticity from other tests.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Young's Modulus

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Grout or mud density determined using a mud balance
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Mud Balance Density

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Value from Standard Penetration Test (SPT) to define advancement in terms of blows required to drive a specific sampler I foot into the soil using a hammer that provides a specific impact energy.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: N-Value (Raw)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Calculated value that corrects the value of the Standard Penetration Blow Count (N), to account for energy of the hammer (specifically normalized to 60% energy) and specific overburden conditions (specifically to an overburden stress of 1 ton per square foot).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: N1,60

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Calculated value that corrects the value of the Standard Penetration Blow Count (N-value), to account for energy of the hammer (specifically normalized to 60% energy).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: N60

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A value of true for this property indiates that no plastic limit can be . In such cases the value of the plastic limit should be left empty or set to the null value, and the value of non_plastic set to true.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Non Plastic

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A calculation that reflects the maximum past consolidation test that the in situ soil has been subjected to compared to the current vertical overburden stress on the sample in the field. This value is usually measured from the one-dimensional consolidation tests. Often referenced as the parameter to track the stress history.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Overconsolidation Ratio

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The velocity of a p-wave (Vp). P-waves (primary waves) are compressional waves that are longitudinal in nature.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Primary Compression Wave Velocity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A-Reading corrected for the DA membrane stiffness at 0.05 mm expansion, the 0.05 mm expansion itself and the gauge pressure deviation from zero. This corrected pressure is referred to as p0. This is an intermediate result from a flat plate dilatometer test.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: P0 Reading

diggs:Definition.gml:description: B-Reading corrected for the DB membrane stiffness at 1.10 mm expansion and the gauge pressure deviation from zero. This corrected pressure is referred to as p1. This is an intermediate result from a flat plate dilatometer test.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: P1 Reading

diggs:Definition.gml:description: C-Reading corrected for the DA membrane stiffness at 0.05 mm expansion and the gauge pressure deviation from zero. This corrected pressure is referred to as p2. This is an intermediate result from a flat plate dilatometer test.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: P2 Reading

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The distance that a tool travels for a given number of hammer blows.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Penetration Increment

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage by weight of particles larger than 3 inches (75 mm) and smaller than 12 inches (300 mm)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Percent Cobbles

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage of particles that pass through the #200 sieve (<0.075-mm).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Percent Fines

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage of particles that are retained on the #4 and larger sizes (>4.75 mm).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Percent Gravel

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage of particles thatpass the #4 sivve and are retained on the #200 sieve (<4.75 mm and >0.075-mm).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Percent Sand

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The percentage of particles smaller than 0.075 mm (No. 200 sieve) and larger than 0.002 mm and have a plotting position below the A-line on the plasticity chart as well as a plasticity index less than 4. The percent silt is determined by the difference between the total percent passing the No. 200 sieve (fines) and the percent clay (determined through plasticity testing of the fines fraction).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Percent Silt

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A meassure of how acidic or basic a soil or water is.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: pH

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measures volatile organic compounds and other gases, expressed in parts per million.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Photoionization Detector Result

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The plastic limit (PL) is the water content where soil transitions between brittle and plastic behavior.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Plastic Limit

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The plasticity index (PI) is a measure of the plasticity of a soil. The plasticity index is a measure of the range of water contents where the soil exhibits plastic properties. The PI is the difference between the liquid limit and the plastic limit (PI = LL-PL). (Soils with a high PI tend to be clay, those with a lower PI tend to be silt, and those with a PI of 0 (non-plastic) tend to have little or no silt or clay.)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Plasticity Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Point Load Test produces the Point Load Test Index (Is50), which can be correlated with the uniaxial compressive strength (UCS) of rock.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Point Load Test Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Ratio of the transverse contraction of a body to its longitudinal extension when stretched. Typical values in minerals are from 0.15 to 0.3 (Carbonates:0.15, Sandstones:0.2, Shales:0.25).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Poisson Ratio

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The value of pore pressure measured in the field after dissipation of induced excess pore pressure. Could also be from CPTu test
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Equilibrium Pore Water Pressure (U0)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The pore-water pressure acting at the center of the membrane before the insertion of the DMT blade (often assumed as hydrostatic below the water table surface).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Estimated Pore Water Pressure

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measured pore pressure from u1 transducer on tip.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Pore Water Pressure (U1)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measured pore pressure from u2 transducer behind tip.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Pore Water Pressure (U2)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measured pore pressure from u3 transducer behind sleeve.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Pore Water Pressure (U3)

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Result from a Consolidation Test. This test is performed to determine the magnitude and rate of void ratio change for a laterally confined soil specimen that is subjected to different vertical pressures. From the measured data, the consolidation curve (pressure-void ratio relationship) can be plotted. This specific value is used for a specific portion of the log vertical pressure - void ratio curve to signify the largest value of stress that sample has experienced before the performance of this test. It is a calculation results usually obtained by a construction technique using laboratory test results.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Preconsolidation Pressure

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Value derived from a pressure filtration test
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Pressure Filtration Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Result from a Consolidation Test. This test is performed to determine the magnitude and rate of void ratio change for a laterally confined soil specimen that is subjected to different vertical pressures. From the measured data, the consolidation curve (pressure-void ratio relationship) can be plotted. This specific value is used for a specific portion of the log vertical pressure - void ratio curve to signify a response due to the unloading and reloading of a sample that is on the virgin curve.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Recompression Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A 'measure of the ability of chemical/biochemical systems to oxidize (lose electrons) or reduce (gain electrons).
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Redox Potential

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The density of a granular specimen relative to its maximum and minimum density (or void ratio)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Density, Relative

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A measure of the resisting power of a specified material to the flow of an electric current.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Electrical Resistivity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The open space in a rock divided by the total rock volume.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Rock Porosity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Schmidt Hardness Test utilizes a hammer mass launched against an impact plunger. The amount of hammer mass rebound depends on the hardness of the test piece. This rebound amount is then shown on a scale of 10 to 100.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Schmidt Hardness Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: the ratio of the strength of the soil in the undisturbed state to that of the soil in the remolded state.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Sensitivity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Setting time for grout
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Set Time

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The peak shear resistance of an intact specimen when pore fluid pressures, generated during the course of shearing the soil, are able to dissipate during shearing. It also applies where no pore water exists in the soil (the soil is dry) and hence pore fluid pressures are negligible.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Peak Drained Shear Strength

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The peak shear strength of an intact specimen when no volume change is allowed during the tests. The value can be measured in the lab and in the field. In both cases, the value can be calculated from different tests.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Peak Undrained Shear Strength

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A measure of the shear strength of the soil for which the shear stress remains essentially constant with increasing shear displacement andwhen no volume change is allowed during the tests.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Residual Undrained Shear Strength

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The velocity of a shear wave (Vs); a shear wave is a type of seismic wave in which the particle motion is perpendicular to the direction of propagation in a horizontal plane ; also called S-wave or secondary wave.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Shear Velocity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The height of the rebound travel of the Scleroscope hammer is measured on a graduated scale. The scale of the rebound is arbitrarily chosen and consists on Shore units, divided into 100 parts, which represent the average rebound from pure hardened high-carbon steel. The scale is continued higher than 100 to include metals having greater hardness.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Shore Hardness Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The amount of grout shrinkage, reported as a percentage of total volume
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Shrinkage

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The shrinkage limit (SL) is the water content below which a soil undergoes no further volume change.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Shrinkage Limit

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The ratio of a given volume change expressed as a percentage of the dry volume to the corresponding change in water content above the shrinkage limit.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Shrinkage Ratio

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Slake Durability Index predicts the long-term durability of the rock specimens, to establish weathering and degradation characteristics of each rock type, and to assess the impact of water on the rock degradation.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Slake Durability Index

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Value of stress measured on sleeve of cone during penetration
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Sleeve Friction

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Amount of slump of grout sample
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Slump

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Soil moisture content measured by sensor (eg CPT)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Soil Moisture Content

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Soil suction value
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Soil Suction

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A value derived from a dilatometer test, using the dilatometer modulus and material index.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Soil Type

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The apparent specific gravity is designated Ga and is the ratio of the weight in air of a unit volume of the impermeable portion of aggregate to the weight in air of an equal volume of distilled water, both at a stated temperature. The impermeable portion of a porous material, such as most large soil grains, includes the solid material plus impermeable pores or voids within the particles.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Apparent Specific Gravity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The bulk specific gravity is designated Gm and is the ratio of the weight in air of a unit volume of aggregate (including permeable and impermeable voids in the particles, but not the voids between the particles) to the weight of an equal volume of distilled water at a stated temperature.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Bulk Specific Gravity

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The specific gravity of solids (Gs) is the bulk density of the solid particles relative to the density of water. It is a required parameter to assess void ratio. Its value is a function of the mineralogy of the solid particles. It is commonly assumed by geotechnical engineers.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Specific Gravity of Solids

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Sulfate content by lab testing (corrosivity series)
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Sulfate Content
diggs:Definition.diggs:quantityClass: amount of substance per amount of substance

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The contraction of a gel accompanied by the separating out of liquid. It is calculated as a percent of volume or mass loss.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Syneresis

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The syneresis value of a gel specimen divided by its surface area; accounts for variability in syneresis of a gel depending on the amount of the gel exposed to air. Calculated as mass loss divided by surface area
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Surface Area Normalized Syneresis

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Time until pore pressure reaches the halfway pressure (u50) between starting dynamic pore pressure and equilibrium pore pressure
diggs:Definition.gml:name: T50

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measured temperature
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Temperature

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A measure of the resistance of aggregate crushing.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Ten Percent Fines Value

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Thrust force required to advance the dilatometer to the test depth. This force is exclusive of soil or other friction along the push rods. This thrust is referred to as qd.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Thrust

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Time of measurement
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Time

diggs:Definition.gml:description: A measure of stress measured at tip of cone during penetration
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Tip Resistance

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Tip resistance corrected for u2 pore pressure measurement
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Corrected Tip Resistance

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Torque: The rotational force applied by the drill rig.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Torque

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Pore pressure midway between dynamic pore pressure and equilibrium pore pressure
diggs:Definition.gml:name: U50

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Unit weight of a soil mass is the ratio of the total weight of soil to the total volume of soil.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Unit Weight

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The Unified Soil Classification group name, including any modifiers as defined in Figures 1,2 and 3 of ASTM D2487 or Figures 1 and 2 of ASTM D2488, eg "Silty sand" or "Gravelly silt with sand".
diggs:Definition.gml:name: USCS Group Name

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The two-letter symbol of soil type of the Unified Soil Classification System, used in engineering and geology to describe the texture and grain size of a soil.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: USCS Group Symbol

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The two letter symbol of soil type of the Unified Soil Classification System of material passing 425 micron screen
diggs:Definition.gml:name: USCS Symbol Passing 425 Screen

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Total vertical stress at the center of the membrane before the insertion of the DMT blade, generally calculated from unit weights estimated using the DMT results.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Total Vertical Stress

diggs:Definition.gml:description: The decrease in volume of a soil mass when the water content is reduced from a given percentage to the shrinkage limit and which is expressed as percentage of dry volume of the soil mass.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Volumetric Shrinkage

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Descriptive result of a washout test
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Washout Result

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Also referred to as moisture content, this is the mass of water divided by the mass of the solids, expressed as a percentage. Use of this parameter is for natural conditions. Determined in a laboratory or via sensor.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Natural Water Content

diggs:Definition.gml:description: This is a result of a compaction test. It is defined as the moisture content at the maximum dry unit weight as measured when a specific type and amount of energy is used for the compaction test. This is also the value of the compaction moisture content when the soils achieves the maximum dry unit weight.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Optimum Water Content

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measured depth to water below datum, typically directly observed or computed from a pressure transducer
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Water Depth

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Depth to water calculated from measured equilibrium pore pressure. Note: it is preferable to use water_depth as the propertyClass with the measurementTechnique property of the Property element set to "calculated", instead.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Calculated Depth To Water

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Estimate of water depth from insitu measurement (eg CPT, DMT). Note: it is preferable to use water_depth as the propertyClass with the measurementTechnique property qualifer (eg. "extrapolated". "inferred"), instead.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Estimated Water Depth

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Measured elevation of water level, typically directly observed or computed from a pressure transducer
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Water elevation

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Water elevation calculated from measured equilibrium pore pressure. Note: it is preferable to use water_elevation as the propertyClass with the measurementTechnique property of the Property element set to "calculated", instead.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Calculated Water Elevation

diggs:Definition.gml:description: Estimate of water elevation from insitu measurement (eg CPT, DMT). Note: it is preferable to use water_elevation as the propertyClass with the measurementTechnique property qualifer (eg. "extrapolated". "inferred"), instead.
diggs:Definition.gml:name: Estimated Water Elevaton
